    <!-- Main Content: Do's and What Not To Do -->
    <div class="row align-items-center">
      <!-- Left Column: Guidelines -->
      <div class="col-md-6">
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-3">Immediate Steps:</h3>
        <ol class="fs-5">
          <li>
            <strong>Call Emergency Services:</strong> Dial your local emergency number (e.g., 112 or 911) immediately.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Start CPR:</strong> If you are trained, begin chest compressions immediatelyâ€”aim for at least 100 compressions per minute at a depth of about 2 inches.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Use an AED if Available:</strong> If an Automated External Defibrillator (AED) is nearby, turn it on and follow its voice instructions.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Continue CPR:</strong> Do not stop until emergency responders arrive or the person shows signs of life.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Stay Calm and Safe:</strong> Ensure your safety and that of the victim. Keep trying until help arrives.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mt-4 mb-3">What Not To Do:</h3>
        <ul class="fs-5">
          <li>Do not delay calling for help.</li>
          <li>Avoid administering medications unless properly trained.</li>
          <li>Do not attempt untrained advanced life support techniques.</li>
          <li>Do not allow panic or distractions to interfere with your actions.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-muted mt-3">
          <em>Note:</em> This guide is for emergency use only and does not replace professional medical training.
        </p>
      </div>
      
